53	f	2017-09-21 19:21:59.259059+01	{"body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>During their travels through western Europe (1763-1768) and in Italy (1769-1773), the Mozarts collected souvenirs of the places they had visited, the monuments, holy places, natural wonders and people they had seen or met. In part these souvenirs served to remind them later of their journeys\\\\u2014to evoke memories of where they had been and who they had met\\\\u2014and in part they were intended to be shown to friends and acquaintances where they had been and to supplement their descriptions of those people and places with visual imagery and objects.\\\\u00a0</p><h3>Naples and Mount Vesuvius</h3><p>Between 14 May and 25 June 1770, Mozart and his father visited Naples. A major tourist site there \\\\u2014 and one they were encouraged to visit by their acquaintance William Hamilton \\\\u2014 was Vesuvius. Leopold first mentioned the volcano in a letter to his wife of 29 May 1770: \\\\u2018Vesuvius\\\\u2019\\\\u00a0hasn`t given me the pleasure of burning or, rather, spitting fire. Only very occasionally does one see a little smoke. But we shall shortly be seeing it at close quarters.\\\\u2019 They had a better view of an eruption on 5 June, when Mozart wrote to his sister,\\\\u00a0 \\\\u2018Smoke is pouring out of Vesuvius\\\\u00a0today, odds fish and zounds,\\\\u2019 and they visited the volcano on 18-19 June, when Leopold Mozart wrote:\\\\u00a0 \\\\u2018On Monday and Tuesday etc. we`re going to take a closer look at Vesuvius, Pompeii and Herculaneum - the towns that are currently being excavated - and admire the curiosities that have already been discovered and also take a look at Caserta\\\\u00a0etc. and Capo di Monte etc.\\\\u2019 \\\\u00a0<br/></p><p><br/><embed alt=\\\\\\": Undated engraving owned by the Mozart\\\\u2019s, Venus erupting (Salzburg, Salzburg Museum)\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"2\\\\\\"/><br/><br/>Mozart and his father purchased or were given two souvenirs of their encounter with Vesuvius, some lava and a copper engraving that shows a close-up view of the erupting volcano. The lava they acquired does not survive; the engraving they purchased or were given survives in the library of the Salzburg Museum:</p><embed alt=\\\\\\"Lava\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"right\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"3\\\\\\"/><p>Some souvenirs acquired by, or given to, the Mozarts on their tours through Europe are known only from descriptions in the\\\\u00a0Mozart family letters.\\\\u00a0</p><p>Others, though, and in particular topographical engravings from London and Naples, survive.\\\\u00a0</p><p></p>\\"}]", "locked": false, "title": "The Mozarts as Collectors of Souvenirs", "numchild": 2, "show_in_menus": false, "live": true, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "depth": 4, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-09-21T18:12:01.281Z", "has_unpublished_changes": true, "content_type": 34, "path": "0001000100020001", "owner": 1, "pk": 11, "first_published_at": "2017-06-15T14:28:20.323Z", "url_path": "/home/souvenirs/second-example-page/", "expired": false, "slug": "second-example-page", "expire_at": null, "go_live_at": null}	\N	11	3
