57	f	2017-09-21 19:43:19.175226+01	{"body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>By explicitly associating Mozart\\\\u2019s portrait with his printed music, and the autograph of K20 with a \\\\u2018sounding\\\\u2019 piece of music \\\\u2013 the British Museum\\\\u2019s description of the sonatas and manuscript as \\\\u2018musical performances\\\\u2019 is significant in this respect \\\\u2013 Leopold Mozart effectively makes both the physical objects, the music print and autograph, and the immaterial object itself, the music, souvenirs. To fully understand this notion in an eighteenth-century context, it is necessary to understand the notion of \\\\u2018souvenir\\\\u2019.</p><p><br/></p><p>Prior to the nineteenth century, the word souvenir \\\\u2014 now generally understood as \\\\u2018something that is given or kept as a reminder of a place, person, event, etc.; a memento, a keepsake; spec. a (typically small and inexpensive) item designed for sale to tourists and having some association with the place visited\\\\u2019 (OED) \\\\u2014 was rarely used to refer to a material object. Derived from the French souvenir, \\\\u00a0it represented memory associated with feeling, whether that memory was buried deep in the unconscious and had to be willed into consciousness, or whether it was on the surface of consciousness, ever-present.\\\\u00a0</p><p><br/></p><p>In both German and English writings from the eighteenth century, the word souvenir appears in passages that, unlike the rest of the text, are entirely in French, or it appears in a font (italic or roman, depending on the original language) that distinguishes it as French in both origin and meaning.</p><p><br/></p>\\"}]", "locked": false, "title": "Eighteenth-century understandings of the word and idea \\u2018souvenir\\u2019", "numchild": 0, "show_in_menus": false, "live": true, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "depth": 4, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-06-15T14:15:17.857Z", "has_unpublish