34	f	2017-09-18 16:48:03.611337+01	{"body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Later, during\\\\nthe family visits to Paris in 1763-1764 and London in 1764-1765, Leopold\\\\nproduced both visual and musical objects as souvenirs of Wolfgang Amadeus,\\\\nincluding portraits and printed music, and, in the case of the motet <i>God is our Refuge</i> K20, Mozart\\\\u2019s\\\\nautograph manuscript.\\\\u00a0</p>\\"}]", "locked": false, "title": "Examples of souvenirs produced by the Mozarts", "numchild": 0, "show_in_menus": false, "live": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "depth": 5, "latest_revision_created_at": null, "has_unpublished_changes": false, "content_type": 34, "path": "00010001000200020001", "owner": 3, "pk": 14, "first_published_at": null, "url_path": "/home/souvenirs/2-mozarts-producers-souvenirs/examples-souvenirs-produced-mozarts/", "expired": false, "slug": "examples-souvenirs-produced-mozarts", "expire_at": null, "go_live_at": null}	\N	14	3
212	f	2017-10-05 23:38:12.200493+01	{"search_description": "", "owner": 3, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-10-05T22:38:05.447Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "The Mozarts as Producers of Souvenirs", "seo_title": "", "draft_title": "The Mozarts as Producers of Souvenirs", "live": true, "last_published_at": "2017-10-03T20:19:46.557Z", "has_unpublished_changes": true, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"59adc82e-8670-454f-9c1f-760379689655\\", \\"value\\": \\"The\\\\nidea of collecting souvenirs was not new during the eighteenth century. Souvenir\\\\ncollecting had a long history, originally of relics and other religious-related\\\\nobjects but later painted plates, wooden caskets, glasses and walking sticks\\\\nfrom spas and, once archaeological digs became common, relics from antiquity.<a href=\\\\\\"#_ftn1\\\\\\">[1]</a> Musical\\\\nsouvenirs, however \\\\u2014 aside from portraits of composers and performers, often\\\\ncollected not as souvenirs of acquaintance but for personal, artistic\\\\nedification and inspiration \\\\u2014 were uncommon.<p><br/>\\\\n\\\\n</p><hr/>\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n<p>\\\\n\\\\n</p><p><a href=\\\\\\"#_ftnref1\\\\\\">[1]</a> See Godfrey Evans, <i>Souvenirs\\\\nfrom Roman Times to the Present Day</i> (Edinburgh: NMS Publishing, 1999).</p>\\\\n\\\\n<p></p>\\\\n\\\\n<p></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"35878b54-c9d1-490e-b77e-dc3975350be8\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Leopold Mozart appears to have been among the first\\\\nmusicians to produce a souvenir that served not only as a memento of a visit to\\\\na particular place, but also made of an immaterial object, a piece of music, a\\\\nsouvenir. His <i>Der Morgen und der Abend\\\\nden Inwohnern der Hochf\\\\u00fcrstl. Residenz=Stadt Salzburg melodisch und harmonisch\\\\nangek\\\\u00fcndigt </i>(Augsburg, 1759) includes not only works composed for a\\\\nmechanical organ, the so-called <i>Hornwerk</i>\\\\nat the Hohensalzburg fortress, first constructed in 1502, but also a brief\\\\nhistory of the fortress.\\\\u00a0\\\\u00a0<br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"Franz Anton Danreiter, Hohensalzburg, engraving c1735 (Salzburg, Universit\\\\u00e4tsbibliothek)\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"63\\\\\\"/><br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"b12b4f08-0216-4e61-ac49-4106efaa3adc\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The first souvenir he produced of Wolfgang was an\\\\nengraved portrait of the family \\\\u2014 Wolfgang, Mozart\\\\u2019s sister Nannerl and Leopold\\\\nperforming \\\\u2014 that was sold with Mozart\\\\u2019s earliest compositions and\\\\nwidely-distributed throughout the 1770s.<br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"Carmontelle, Leopold Mozart with Wolfgang and Anna Maria, engraving (by Christian Mechel), Paris 1764 (British Museum, London)\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"40\\\\\\"/><br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"c0a885c4-7f5c-4c2d-bb4d-41d95130d2f9\\", \\"value\\": \\"<img/>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"8f216167-b003-4f36-9775-479f84143fd9\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>While the portrait was in effect a souvenir, and by\\\\nassociation the printed editions of Mozart\\\\u2019s sonatas became souvenirs as well,\\\\nan understanding that an immaterial object, the music itself, can serve as a\\\\nsouvenir as it was understood in the eighteenth century, is most explicit in\\\\nthe case of Mozart\\\\u2019s motet <i>God is our\\\\nRefuge</i> K20, the autograph manuscript of which was given to the British\\\\nMuseum in July 1765. The Museum understood the manuscript, and with it the\\\\nwork, to be \\\\u2018musical performances\\\\u2019.</p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"W. A. Mozart, God is our Refuge K20, autograph manuscript\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"5\\\\\\"/>\\\\u00a0</p>\\"}]", "numchild": 1, "content_type": 34, "show_in_menus": false, "path": "0001000100020003", "url_path": "/home/souvenirs/mozarts-producers-souvenirs/", "expired": false, "slug": "mozarts-producers-souvenirs", "locked": false, "pk": 13, "depth": 4, "first_published_at": "2017-09-19T16:04:12.794Z", "expire_at": null, "live_revision": 156}	\N	13	4
36	f	2017-09-19 17:04:12.761048+01	{"body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"The\\\\nidea of collecting souvenirs was not new during the eighteenth century. Souvenir\\\\ncollecting had a long history, originally of relics and other religious-related\\\\nobjects but later painted plates, wooden caskets, glasses and walking sticks\\\\nfrom spas and, once archaeological digs became common, relics from antiquity.<a href=\\\\\\"#_ftn1\\\\\\">[1]</a> Musical\\\\nsouvenirs, however \\\\u2014 aside from portraits of composers and performers, often\\\\ncollected not as souvenirs of acquaintance but for personal, artistic\\\\nedification and inspiration \\\\u2014 were uncommon.<p><br/>\\\\n\\\\n</p><hr/>\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n<p>\\\\n\\\\n</p><p><a href=\\\\\\"#_ftnref1\\\\\\">[1]</a> See Godfrey Evans, <i>Souvenirs\\\\nfrom Roman Times to the Present Day</i> (Edinburgh: NMS Publishing, 1999).</p>\\\\n\\\\n<p></p>\\\\n\\\\n<p></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Leopold\\\\nMozart appears to have been among the first musicians to produce a souvenir\\\\nthat served not only the traditional souvenir function, as a memento of a visit\\\\nto a particular place, but also made of an immaterial object, a piece of music,\\\\na souvenir. One of the chief tourist attractions in Salzburg was a mechanical\\\\norgan, the so-called <i>Hornwerk</i> at the\\\\nHohensalzburg fortress, first constructed in 1502.\\\\u00a0</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>As\\\\nan open-air instrument, it frequently required repair and in 1753 the Salzburg\\\\ncourt organ maker, Rochus Egedacher, was commissioned to renovate and expand\\\\nthe mechanism. Egedacher built a new barrel with twelve pieces of music, one\\\\nfor each month of the year. Five of them were composed by the court music\\\\ndirector, Ernst Eberlin, and the rest by Leopold Mozart.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Leopold\\\\nMozart published the pieces in 1759 but not merely as a collection of musical\\\\npieces. Possibly uniquely among early- to mid-eighteenth-century music prints, <i>Der Morgen und der Abend den Inwohnern der\\\\nHochf\\\\u00fcrstl. Residenz=Stadt Salzburg melodisch und harmonisch angek\\\\u00fcndigt </i>(Augsburg,\\\\n1759) was intended as a souvenir for visitors to Salzburg, since in addition to\\\\nscores of the pieces for the months of the year, it also included a lengthy prefatory\\\\ntext, a potted history of the Salzburg fortress.</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"value\\": \\"<embed alt=\\\\\\"Der Morgen und der Abend\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"4\\\\\\"/>\\"}]", "locked": false, "title": "The Mozarts as Producers of Souvenirs", "numchild": 1, "show_in_menus": false, "live": false, "seo_title": "", "search_description": "", "depth": 4, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-09-18T15:46:03.339Z", "has_unpublished_changes": true, "content_type": 34, "path": "0001000100020002", "owner": 3, "pk": 13, "first_published_at": null, "url_path": "/home/souvenirs/2-mozarts-producers-souvenirs/", "expired": false, "slug": "mozarts-producers-souvenirs", "expire_at": null, "go_live_at": null}	\N	13	2
203	f	2017-10-05 23:25:23.227994+01	{"search_description": "", "owner": 4, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-10-05T22:25:08.469Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "Engravings of London purchased by, or given to, the Mozarts, 1764-5", "seo_title": "", "draft_title": "Engravings of London purchased by, or given to, the Mozarts, 1764-5", "live": false, "last_published_at": null, "has_unpublished_changes": true, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"0f1d1bea-b02e-47f9-80c2-270ab390b23e\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>In his letter of 28 June 1764 (\\\\u2018. . . in due course I shall\\\\n\\\\u2013 God willing \\\\u2013 show you some copper engravings not only of these places [in\\\\nLondon] but of many other things both in Paris and London. You can then have a\\\\nfuller explanation of them. I\\\\u2019ve left a number of copper engravings in Paris\\\\nthat are worth 2 louis d\\\\u2019or.\\\\u2019) Leopold writes of engravings\\\\nof the sights of Paris and London that he collected during the family\\\\u2019s tour to\\\\nboth cities in 1763-1764. The engravings from Paris are lost. The engravings\\\\nfrom London, however, survive (possibly incompletely) in the library of the\\\\nSalzburg Museum. The catalogue card for the Museum Carolino Augusteum, where\\\\nthe engravings were found, prior to their transfer to the Salzburg Museum,\\\\nreads: \\\\u2018Kupferstiche aus Mozartschen Besitz/ Jb. 1850. UB 3227 I / III Seite\\\\n17ff. Pkt 2 a-e \\\\u2018. A further note, in an unidentified hand, reads: \\\\u2018a) Eine\\\\nAnzahl Kupferstiche, welche der Vater Leopold Mozart auf seiner Kunstreise im\\\\nJahre 1763 in London, Br\\\\u00fcssel, Paris und Neapel eingekauft, wobei sich auch\\\\nsein englisches in London gekauftes Gebetb\\\\u00fcchlein befindet.\\\\u2019 The Brussels,\\\\nParis and Rome engravings do not survive; nor does the small prayer book. It is\\\\nlikely that the surviving engravings derive from the estate of Mozart\\\\u2019s sister,\\\\nNannerl, the inventory of which included:</p><p>\\\\u00a0</p><p>28\\\\nitalienische Prospekte mit Gl\\\\u00e4sern und Rahmen</p><p>2\\\\nHoll\\\\u00e4nderst\\\\u00fccke</p><p>12\\\\nLandschaften</p><p>2\\\\nLandschaften Tower und Calais vorstellend</p><p>2 do\\\\nitaliensiche</p><p>3\\\\nPropekte der Stadt London<a>[1]</a></p><p>\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n</p><p><br/>\\\\n\\\\n</p><hr/>\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n<p>\\\\n\\\\n</p><p><a>[1]</a> See Rudolph Angerm\\\\u00fcller, \\\\u2018Testament,\\\\nKodizill, Nachtrag und Sperrelation der Freifrau Maria Anna von Berchtold zu\\\\nSonnenburg, geb. Mozart (1751-1829)', Mozart-Jahrbuch 1986, 121.</p>\\\\n\\\\n<p></p>\\\\n\\\\n<p></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"52a6d391-03c9-4045-b29a-896ec0b54fec\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p><embed alt=\\\\\\"The North Prospect of LONDON taken from the Bowling Green at Islington\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"58\\\\\\"/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"A View of the late Celebrated Mr. Popes House at Twickenham\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"57\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"A View of the New Bridge at Westminster\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"56\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"A View of the Custom House, and part of the Tower of London\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"55\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"A View of Lord Burlington's House at CHISWICK\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"54\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"A View of St. Mary-le-Bone, from the Bason\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"53\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"A View of Sion House, over against Richmond in SURRY\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"52\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"A View of Richmond Hill from the Earl of Cholmondelly's\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"50\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"Lambeth / The Archbishop of Canterbury's Palace\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"49\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"A View of the Bridge at Walton upon Thames in SURRY, Twenty Miles from LONDON\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"48\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"A View of Fulham Bridge from Putney\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"47\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"The South East Prospect of WESTMINSTER\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"46\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"A View of the Foundling Hospital\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"45\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"A View of theRoyal Hospital at Chelsea, &amp; the Rotunda in Ranelagh Gardens\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"44\\\\\\"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"The South West Prospect of London. From Somerset Gardens to the Tower\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"43\\\\\\"/><br/></p>\\"}]", "numchild": 0, "content_type": 34, "show_in_menus": false, "path": "000100010002000200020002", "url_path": "/home/souvenirs/second-example-page/surviving-souvenirs/engravings-london-purchased-or-given-mozarts-1764-5/", "expired": false, "slug": "engravings-london-purchased-or-given-mozarts-1764-5", "locked": false, "pk": 38, "depth": 6, "first_published_at": null, "expire_at": null, "live_revision": null}	\