251	f	2017-10-10 10:39:16.055607+01	{"search_description": "", "owner": 3, "latest_revision_created_at": "2017-10-05T22:38:12.200Z", "go_live_at": null, "title": "The Mozarts as Producers of Souvenirs", "seo_title": "", "draft_title": "The Mozarts as Producers of Souvenirs", "live": true, "last_published_at": "2017-10-05T22:38:12.282Z", "has_unpublished_changes": false, "body": "[{\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"c57971b1-eb15-45f1-a250-0ee0bf0179c4\\", \\"value\\": \\"The idea of collecting souvenirs was not new during the eighteenth century. Souvenir collecting had a long history, originally of relics and other religious-related objects but later painted plates, wooden caskets, glasses and walking sticks from spas and, once archaeological digs became common, relics from antiquity.<a href=\\\\\\"#_ftn1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0Musical souvenirs, however \\\\u2014 aside from portraits of composers and performers, often collected not as souvenirs of acquaintance but for personal, artistic edification and inspiration \\\\u2014 were uncommon.<p><br/></p><hr/><p></p><p><a href=\\\\\\"#_ftnref1\\\\\\">[1]</a>\\\\u00a0See Godfrey Evans,\\\\u00a0<i>Souvenirs from Roman Times to the Present Day</i>\\\\u00a0(Edinburgh: NMS Publishing, 1999).</p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"59adc82e-8670-454f-9c1f-760379689655\\", \\"value\\": \\"The\\\\nidea of collecting souvenirs was not new during the eighteenth century. Souvenir\\\\ncollecting had a long history, originally of relics and other religious-related\\\\nobjects but later painted plates, wooden caskets, glasses and walking sticks\\\\nfrom spas and, once archaeological digs became common, relics from antiquity.<a href=\\\\\\"#_ftn1\\\\\\">[1]</a> Musical\\\\nsouvenirs, however \\\\u2014 aside from portraits of composers and performers, often\\\\ncollected not as souvenirs of acquaintance but for personal, artistic\\\\nedification and inspiration \\\\u2014 were uncommon.<p><br/>\\\\n\\\\n</p><hr/>\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n\\\\n<p>\\\\n\\\\n</p><p><a href=\\\\\\"#_ftnref1\\\\\\">[1]</a> See Godfrey Evans, <i>Souvenirs\\\\nfrom Roman Times to the Present Day</i> (Edinburgh: NMS Publishing, 1999).</p>\\\\n\\\\n<p></p>\\\\n\\\\n<p></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"35878b54-c9d1-490e-b77e-dc3975350be8\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>Leopold Mozart appears to have been among the first\\\\nmusicians to produce a souvenir that served not only as a memento of a visit to\\\\na particular place, but also made of an immaterial object, a piece of music, a\\\\nsouvenir. His <i>Der Morgen und der Abend\\\\nden Inwohnern der Hochf\\\\u00fcrstl. Residenz=Stadt Salzburg melodisch und harmonisch\\\\nangek\\\\u00fcndigt </i>(Augsburg, 1759) includes not only works composed for a\\\\nmechanical organ, the so-called <i>Hornwerk</i>\\\\nat the Hohensalzburg fortress, first constructed in 1502, but also a brief\\\\nhistory of the fortress.\\\\u00a0\\\\u00a0<br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"Franz Anton Danreiter, Hohensalzburg, engraving c1735 (Salzburg, Universit\\\\u00e4tsbibliothek)\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"63\\\\\\"/><br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"b12b4f08-0216-4e61-ac49-4106efaa3adc\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>The first souvenir he produced of Wolfgang was an\\\\nengraved portrait of the family \\\\u2014 Wolfgang, Mozart\\\\u2019s sister Nannerl and Leopold\\\\nperforming \\\\u2014 that was sold with Mozart\\\\u2019s earliest compositions and\\\\nwidely-distributed throughout the 1770s.<br/></p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"Carmontelle, Leopold Mozart with Wolfgang and Anna Maria, engraving (by Christian Mechel), Paris 1764 (British Museum, London)\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"40\\\\\\"/><br/></p>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"c0a885c4-7f5c-4c2d-bb4d-41d95130d2f9\\", \\"value\\": \\"<img/>\\"}, {\\"type\\": \\"paragraph\\", \\"id\\": \\"8f216167-b003-4f36-9775-479f84143fd9\\", \\"value\\": \\"<p>While the portrait was in effect a souvenir, and by\\\\nassociation the printed editions of Mozart\\\\u2019s sonatas became souvenirs as well,\\\\nan understanding that an immaterial object, the music itself, can serve as a\\\\nsouvenir as it was understood in the eighteenth century, is most explicit in\\\\nthe case of Mozart\\\\u2019s motet <i>God is our\\\\nRefuge</i> K20, the autograph manuscript of which was given to the British\\\\nMuseum in July 1765. The Museum understood the manuscript, and with it the\\\\nwork, to be \\\\u2018musical performances\\\\u2019.</p><p><br/></p><p><embed alt=\\\\\\"W. A. Mozart, God is our Refuge K20, autograph manuscript\\\\\\" embedtype=\\\\\\"image\\\\\\" format=\\\\\\"fullwidth\\\\\\" id=\\\\\\"5\\\\\\"/>\\\\u00a0</p>\\"}]", "numchild": 3, "content_type": 34, "show_in_menus": false, "path": "0001000100020003", "url_path": "/home/souvenirs/mozarts-producers-souvenirs/", "expired": false, "slug": "mozarts-producers-souvenirs", "locked": false, "pk": 13, "depth": 4, "first_published_at": "2017-09-19T16:04:12.794Z", "expire_at": null, "live_revision": 212}	\N	13	2
