d ethnic costume in the clothes of\\\\nchambermaids and cooks as well as bourgeois women. The idea of dressing in\\\\nlayers came from traditional rural costumes: over a corset, called a \\\\u201clittle\\\\nbouffant,\\\\u201d a woman wore a short, tight jacket \\\\u2014 a spencer \\\\u2014 and a voluminous\\\\nskirt with an apron.\\\\u2019 Polly Cone, ed., <i>The\\\\nImperial Style: Fashions of the Hapburg Era</i> (New York: Metropolitan Museum\\\\nof Art, 1980), 37</p>\\\\n\\\\n<p></p>\\"}]", "numchild": 0, "content_type": 34, "show_in_menus": false, "path": "00010001000200010006", "url_path": "/home/souvenirs/what-mozart-saw/1781-salzburg-and-vienna-ribbons-and-aprons/", "expired": false, "slug": "1781-salzburg-and-vienna-ribbons-and-aprons", "locked": false, "pk": 28, "depth": 5, "first_published_at": "2017-09-23T21:43:01.068Z", "expire_at": null, "live_revision": 193}	\N	28	3
